Susanna and the other food bank directors start flying to Chicago every few months, sitting down in a room and talking about their own version of the pickle problem.

91
00:06:59,810 --> 00:07:02,371
And pretty soon, Susanna says, they get to the heart of it.

92
00:07:02,811 --> 00:07:06,032
It is a problem for someone else to make decisions for you.

93
00:07:06,572 --> 00:07:06,832
Right?

94
00:07:07,313 --> 00:07:13,799
It is a problem if somebody else is trying to decide whether this is something you need or not when they don't know what's in your inventory.

95
00:07:14,160 --> 00:07:16,302
They don't know what your local donation supply is.

96
00:07:16,402 --> 00:07:21,427
They don't know what donated transportation you've arranged for or what your fundraising is at the moment.

97
00:07:21,847 --> 00:07:29,930
So to have a central office trying to make those decisions far away from those sources of knowledge led to all sorts of mismatches.

98
00:07:30,310 --> 00:07:36,333
When the economists in the room heard Susanna and her colleagues lay out the problem this way, they got very excited.

99
00:07:36,813 --> 00:07:40,754
Susanna remembers one economist in particular named Candace Prendagrest.

100
00:07:41,034 --> 00:07:49,918
Once we were able to lay it out in those clear terms, then Candace from the University of Chicago was able to say, well, sounds like an economic problem to me.

101
00:07:53,091 --> 00:07:56,553
There's this phrase in economics, the local knowledge problem.

102
00:07:56,813 --> 00:07:59,494
And it's why centrally planned economies don't work very well.

103
00:07:59,854 --> 00:08:13,962
No matter how smart the people in control are, whether they're in headquarters or the capital or the castle or whatever, they just don't have the knowledge to decide whether the people out in Alaska should get pickles or oranges.

104
00:08:14,522 --> 00:08:22,486
And when I talked to Canis, the economist who was in the room with Suzanne and the others, he told me the clear answer to the local knowledge problem is a market.

105
00:08:22,906 --> 00:08:25,047
a place where buyers and sellers come together.

106
00:08:25,408 --> 00:08:34,854
Because the beauty of a market, and in particular, the beauty of prices, is they show you how much different people, or in this case, different food banks, value different things.

107
00:08:35,294 --> 00:08:42,199
But Kanna says that roomful of food bankers was not very excited to hear his pitch for the virtues of the free market.

108
00:08:42,720 --> 00:08:48,524
One of the food bankers, a wonderful guy called John Arnold came up to me and said, look, I'm a socialist.

109
00:08:48,904 --> 00:08:49,824
I have no interest in this.

110
00:08:49,905 --> 00:08:51,846
I listen to you, but I don't have any interest in this.

111
00:08:52,258 --> 00:08:58,784
I should mention that John Arnold passed away, but when I ran this quote by Susanna, she said, yeah, I could totally imagine John saying that.

112
00:08:59,385 --> 00:09:02,988
And anyway, John was not the only food banker who was wary of the market.

113
00:09:03,328 --> 00:09:05,470
I think many of them have the following sense.

114
00:09:05,891 --> 00:09:07,352
Markets are sometimes unfair.

115
00:09:07,933 --> 00:09:09,234
It benefits the powerful.

116
00:09:09,574 --> 00:09:10,515
It benefits the wealthy.

117
00:09:10,555 --> 00:09:11,636
It benefits the strong.

118
00:09:12,137 --> 00:09:17,702
Their focus is so much on the others, the ones who've been left behind.

119
00:09:17,982 --> 00:09:19,887
Left behind by markets, by the markets.

120
00:09:19,907 --> 00:09:20,408
By markets.

121
00:09:20,749 --> 00:09:24,798
And their great fear is that whatever we came up with would do the same.

122
00:09:25,199 --> 00:09:27,425
And if it did, they would prefer the old system.

123
00:09:27,715 --> 00:09:32,980
The idea of a market just seems fundamentally contrary to the spirit of food banks.

124
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:36,924
I mean, these are places that give away food for free to hungry people.

125
00:09:37,244 --> 00:09:41,308
And in any case, it wasn't like Feeding America could just sell food to the local food banks.

126
00:09:41,728 --> 00:09:47,754
One problem with that is the food banks in poor areas often have the hardest time raising money from local donors.

127
00:09:47,774 --> 00:09:51,297
They're in poor areas, so they wouldn't have enough money to buy the food.

128
00:09:51,637 --> 00:09:56,285
So Canis and the other economists asked the food bankers, what about fake money?

129
00:09:56,645 --> 00:10:04,098
What if Feeding America created its own little economy and gave out fake money to all the food banks which they could use to buy the food?

130
00:10:04,567 --> 00:10:11,831
Next question they said was, but how do we make sure the neediest get the most food, to which we said we give them the most fake money?

131
00:10:12,251 --> 00:10:18,935
And in some sense, maybe that was one of the early breakthrough moments, which was the idea that the poor can actually be wealthier than the rich.

132
00:10:19,475 --> 00:10:20,236
In fake money.

133
00:10:20,656 --> 00:10:22,057
In fake money, exactly.

134
00:10:22,455 --> 00:10:30,381
You could imagine distributing this fake money to the neediest places and then letting them buy, you know, whatever they want out of this national Feeding America system.

135
00:10:30,801 --> 00:10:33,083
But you still have to solve all these other problems.

136
00:10:33,123 --> 00:10:35,785
You know, what should prices be in this new fake money?

137
00:10:35,985 --> 00:10:37,987
How do you let everybody shop in a way that's fair?

138
00:10:38,327 --> 00:10:41,270
So more flights to Chicago, more meetings with the economists.

139
00:10:41,710 --> 00:10:44,252
And finally, Kanes and his colleagues came up with the big idea.

140
00:10:44,612 --> 00:10:45,153
Kanes said,

141
00:10:45,853 --> 00:10:47,394
Well, how about eBay?

142
00:10:47,955 --> 00:11:05,790
How would it work if we set up a system in which all of the food in truckloads that's donated goes on to a technology platform and the decision as to whether you want it for your food bank is made at the food bank and how much you want it is made by how much you bid on it?

143
00:11:06,612 --> 00:11:07,893
And how did that play in the room?

144
00:11:08,253 --> 00:11:10,475
The clouds opened and the angels sang.

145
00:11:11,376 --> 00:11:17,481
No, that never happened.

146
00:11:17,661 --> 00:11:26,829
Okay, maybe it wasn't quite that biblical, but it was literally this moment in which we just went, we have had a breakthrough.

147
00:11:27,129 --> 00:11:33,555
It was like setting up a whole economy, fake money, prices set by auctions, and with that key twist,

148
00:11:33,935 --> 00:11:38,280
The food banks that fed the most hungry people would get the most fake money.

149
00:11:40,523 --> 00:11:45,488
To see how the system works in real life, I went out to the community food bank in New Jersey last week.

150
00:11:45,829 --> 00:11:47,891
They have this huge warehouse out by the Newark Airport.

151
00:11:48,231 --> 00:11:49,493
Tristan Wallach gave me a tour.

152
00:11:50,407 --> 00:11:52,068
You can see some raisins up here.

153
00:11:52,789 --> 00:11:55,090
Canned salmon, you got some grapefruit juice.

154
00:11:56,231 --> 00:11:57,232
What else do we have there?

155
00:11:57,272 --> 00:11:58,533
We have some tomato sauce.

156
00:11:58,913 --> 00:12:03,036
Tristan says the most recent thing he bought at auction with that fake money is some syrup.

157
00:12:03,296 --> 00:12:08,820
The pancake syrup interested me in particular because I know we just bought some pancake mix.

158
00:12:09,320 --> 00:12:14,382
So it's a moment when syrup was particularly valuable to you because you were a guy with pancake batter but no syrup.

159
00:12:14,562 --> 00:12:15,042
Exactly.

160
00:12:15,463 --> 00:12:20,125
So at least for now that means a lot of people in New Jersey can now have syrup with their pancakes.

161
00:12:20,445 --> 00:12:21,245
We'll cut up here.

162
00:12:21,585 --> 00:12:22,886
We can head back to the office.

163
00:12:23,566 --> 00:12:27,968
The office is a smallish room attached to the warehouse and it's where Tristan bids in these auctions.

164
00:12:28,388 --> 00:12:33,672
We get in there and he opens a browser on his computer, logs into the Feeding America system, and shows me this morning's auction.

165
00:12:34,132 --> 00:12:36,394
Down at the bottom of the page, there's a number in red.

166
00:12:36,774 --> 00:12:39,296
This is like Tristan's bank account of fake money.

167
00:12:39,736 --> 00:12:43,719
The money, by the way, has this warm, fuzzy-sounding name, shares.

168
00:12:44,219 --> 00:12:45,079
What does this say right here?

169
00:12:45,220 --> 00:12:46,941
Yeah, it says available shares.

170
00:12:47,501 --> 00:12:48,642
At the moment, I have 5,439 shares.

171
00:12:48,662 --> 00:12:49,503
I view it as like monopoly money.

172
00:12:53,290 --> 00:12:55,132
except that it has real consequences.

173
00:12:55,652 --> 00:12:59,796
Every day, Feeding America gives Tristan some fake money in his bank account.

174
00:13:00,256 --> 00:13:04,640
And there's a formula so that the food banks that feed the most people will get the most fake money.

175
00:13:04,760 --> 00:13:08,243
Yeah, on a typical day, Tristan's food bank gets a few thousand shares.

176
00:13:08,564 --> 00:13:09,725
You can think of it like an allowance.

177
00:13:09,845 --> 00:13:11,186
And he can treat it like an allowance.

178
00:13:11,326 --> 00:13:14,149
If he wants to spend it every day on something little, he can do that.

179
00:13:14,509 --> 00:13:17,432
If he wants to hoard it and splurge on something big, he can do that too.

180
00:13:17,955 --> 00:13:20,897
Today, he pulls up the oxygen on his computer, looks through the stuff.

181
00:13:20,917 --> 00:13:25,140
There's some phanta grape soda, some polio cheese, and then something catches his eye.

182
00:13:25,380 --> 00:13:26,801
It's a truckload of cereal.

183
00:13:26,901 --> 00:13:30,703
Clicking on here, I can see that there's a lot of corn flakes.

184
00:13:30,903 --> 00:13:32,904
There's a little bit of frosted flakes on here.

185
00:13:33,565 --> 00:13:35,046
There's some kashi cereal.

186
00:13:35,286 --> 00:13:37,307
It's about 100,000 boxes and all.

187
00:13:37,547 --> 00:13:41,630
And he says cereal is something people always want and that he doesn't get enough of from his local donors.

188
00:13:42,052 --> 00:13:45,116
He can't actually see how much the other food banks are bidding.

189
