00:15:05,306 --> 00:15:06,386
Tristan hits refresh.

217
00:15:06,927 --> 00:15:07,807
So we lost it.

218
00:15:08,507 --> 00:15:09,127
You didn't get it.

219
00:15:09,247 --> 00:15:09,768
No.

220
00:15:10,028 --> 00:15:14,949
Someone else won this load with 11,564 shares.

221
00:15:15,250 --> 00:15:19,311
The winner bid twice as much as Tristan, someone in Evansville, Indiana.

222
00:15:21,672 --> 00:15:22,372
Can I see food bank?

223
00:15:22,894 --> 00:15:23,134
Yes, hi.

224
00:15:23,214 --> 00:15:24,636
I'm trying to reach John, please.

225
00:15:25,196 --> 00:15:25,717
This is him.

226
00:15:26,057 --> 00:15:32,043
This is John Strain of the Tri-State Food Bank, proud new owner of 100,000 boxes of cereal.

227
00:15:32,264 --> 00:15:35,487
Was there a particular reason right now that you especially wanted cereal?

228
00:15:35,507 --> 00:15:44,336
I just knew that we were down to basically about a half a turn or full of cereal and it goes, it probably will be gone in the next two weeks.

229
00:15:44,703 --> 00:15:54,029
John actually gets less fake money allowance every day than Tristan, but he'd been saving up for weeks and he was about to run out of cereal, this food that everybody really wants.

230
00:15:54,409 --> 00:15:58,031
At the breakfast, the supper, a midnight, it doesn't matter when you keep cereal, you know.

231
00:15:58,492 --> 00:16:02,054
You eat it dry, you eat it with milk, you know, whatever makes you happy.

232
00:16:02,294 --> 00:16:06,637
He figured it was worth it to go big, spend more than twice the average and get that cereal.

233
00:16:07,045 --> 00:16:11,307
If Tristan, in New Jersey, decides that he really needs cereal, he can save up too.

234
00:16:11,467 --> 00:16:15,189
Put his own monster bit up the next time more corn flakes come up for auction.

235
00:16:15,709 --> 00:16:21,372
John and Tristan are too new to remember much about that old system back when Feeding America just sent people stuff.

236
00:16:21,772 --> 00:16:25,014
But it seems like the new system is definitely an improvement.

237
00:16:25,454 --> 00:16:30,737
Susanna Morgan said the auction system meant they could finally get produce at the food bank in Alaska.

238
00:16:31,157 --> 00:16:36,600
And Canis, the economist, told me even John Arnold, the socialist from Michigan, even he came around in the end.

239
00:16:37,063 --> 00:16:41,371
He went from being the most skeptical to being somebody who actually thought it was worth doing.

240
00:16:41,731 --> 00:16:42,473
Wait, what happened?

241
00:16:43,340 --> 00:16:49,382
I think what he realized was the use of this market would give him access to a lot of really cheap food.

242
00:16:49,622 --> 00:16:57,064
So while other food banks were in bidding wars over cereal, John Arnold could swoop in and pick up the stuff that everybody else was ignoring.

243
00:16:57,444 --> 00:16:59,184
And he became what we call the bottom feeders.

244
00:16:59,504 --> 00:17:03,145
He was one of these guys who'd log in every morning, see what was cheap, get loads of it.

245
00:17:03,825 --> 00:17:09,487
And his solution was essentially the market allows me to get a lot of pounds of food in a way that I did not get before.

246
00:17:09,827 --> 00:17:16,669
And when Canis says John would log in and see what was cheap, he of course means what was cheap in fake money.

247
00:17:17,169 --> 00:17:28,652
And one of the really interesting things that has emerged from this system is just how different prices are in this fake money food bank economy compared to the real money economy we see at the grocery store.

248
00:17:29,055 --> 00:17:32,620
Like peanut butter is incredibly valuable in the food bank economy.

249
00:17:32,880 --> 00:17:36,965
It lasts forever, it doesn't have to be refrigerated, and it is a great source of protein.

250
00:17:37,266 --> 00:17:38,207
Also, kids love it.

251
00:17:38,748 --> 00:17:41,832
A truckload of peanut butter can cost tens of thousands of shares.

252
00:17:42,232 --> 00:17:45,597
Dairy, on the other hand, really cheap in the food bank economy.

253
00:17:46,077 --> 00:17:48,318
Lots of food banks get local donations of dairy.

254
00:17:48,659 --> 00:17:52,061
They often have to move it pretty quickly because it has, you know, short expiration dates.

255
00:17:52,281 --> 00:17:54,482
It's harder to store because you have to keep it refrigerated.

256
00:17:54,842 --> 00:17:59,185
So up in Michigan, Kansas says John Arnold could buy a lot of dairy.

257
00:17:59,605 --> 00:18:03,768
And in the end, John Arnold really helped this system take off all around the country.

258
00:18:04,208 --> 00:18:12,173
He was a very persuasive figure because I think a lot of the other food bank director said, if he's in, I'm in because they thought he was unlikely to be a candidate to go along with this.

259
00:18:12,511 --> 00:18:15,537
If the socialist is in on the market system, how bad could it be?

260
00:18:16,039 --> 00:18:16,399
Exactly.

261
00:18:16,840 --> 00:18:20,307
There was one part of the new system that did not work out.

262
00:18:20,918 --> 00:18:29,863
Yeah, when Canis and Susanna and the others were in that room creating this new system, they figured food banks should be able to sell food to each other for fake money.

263
00:18:30,263 --> 00:18:37,226
So that Idaho food bank with all the potatoes could sell them to Susanna in Alaska and get fake money to buy whatever they needed in Idaho.

264
00:18:37,827 --> 00:18:44,930
But even though the food bankers are okay with buying stuff for fake money, they don't really want to sell stuff to other food banks.

265
00:18:45,410 --> 00:18:48,632
Here's John Strain who bought the cereal for that food bank in Indiana.

266
00:18:48,995 --> 00:18:52,181
If I'm a food bank and I have extra product, I'm going to share with another food bank.

267
00:18:52,281 --> 00:18:54,385
I don't want no extra money, no nothing out of it.

268
00:18:54,785 --> 00:18:58,352
I've shared with five different food banks in the last 60 days.

269
00:18:58,592 --> 00:19:01,137
I just think you should share what you've got if you've got plenty.

270
00:19:01,435 --> 00:19:05,218
So, okay, food bank directors are fundamentally generous people.

271
00:19:05,278 --> 00:19:06,658
It's why they're running food banks, right?

272
00:19:06,678 --> 00:19:10,641
And that is part of the reason this corner of the market never took off.

273
00:19:11,101 --> 00:19:13,963
But Susanna Morgan says, there is something else at work.

274
00:19:14,003 --> 00:19:17,065
There's something subtler, really another kind of economy.

275
00:19:17,205 --> 00:19:19,567
This is a network built on relationships.

276
00:19:19,827 --> 00:19:24,210
If you work at a food bank, she says, you need to have friends at other food banks.

277
00:19:24,648 --> 00:19:27,150
You're going to rely on those people for more than just food.

278
00:19:27,170 --> 00:19:30,813
You're going to rely on those people for stealing their good fundraising practices.

279
00:19:31,253 --> 00:19:35,536
You're going to rely on those people for advertising the positions that you have open.

280
00:19:35,976 --> 00:19:41,720
So those people are your best source of learning and contacts.

281
00:19:41,901 --> 00:19:45,023
And you can use food as one of the ways you nurture those relationships.

282
00:19:45,423 --> 00:19:52,452
Susanna is now running the Oregon Food Bank, and she says she does occasionally use the system to sell food to other food banks, but not often.

283
00:19:52,873 --> 00:19:56,037
She says she would much rather just give it away to another food bank.

284
00:20:03,275 --> 00:20:06,298
That was Stacy Vanick-Smith and Jacob Goldstein from 2015.

