296
00:21:03,432 --> 00:21:07,694
When we see a price tag on a product, we think of it in terms of money.

297
00:21:08,234 --> 00:21:11,315
But in the case of the food banks, the price wasn't about money.

298
00:21:11,696 --> 00:21:12,956
The price was about information.

299
00:21:13,476 --> 00:21:21,440
It was about communicating who wanted what, and it helped to find a balance between the supply of different types of food and the demand for each product.

300
00:21:21,920 --> 00:21:24,261
There was a reason the pickles had a negative price.

301
00:21:24,981 --> 00:21:32,905
So now we wanted to spend a few minutes going over the lessons that we learned in the episode with our two resident economists, Justin Wolfers and Betsy Stevenson.

302
00:21:33,345 --> 00:21:33,966
Excited to do it.

303
00:21:34,306 --> 00:21:35,427
Yeah, it's nice to be here.

304
00:21:35,727 --> 00:21:48,158
You know, the thing that I loved about this episode was when you initially think of economics and auctions, you think of competition, like there are winners and there are losers.

305
00:21:48,938 --> 00:21:57,065
But you realize as you listen to the episode that because everyone wants and needs something different, it's not just about winners and losers.

306
00:21:57,105 --> 00:21:58,667
There's an opportunity to create

307
00:21:59,724 --> 00:22:00,885
more winners, if you will.

308
00:22:01,566 --> 00:22:04,688
So the technical expression for this is economists call this gains from trade.

309
00:22:05,429 --> 00:22:07,131
Stuff gets allocated to the people who want it most.

310
00:22:07,571 --> 00:22:09,152
I'll be honest, I find it kind of magical.

311
00:22:09,593 --> 00:22:11,895
All you have to do is change who gets what.

312
00:22:12,876 --> 00:22:15,598
And here we do it through markets and we create more joy in the world.

313
00:22:16,668 --> 00:22:17,649
Literally, more joy.

314
00:22:18,309 --> 00:22:20,011
Same amount of stuff, more joy.

315
00:22:20,171 --> 00:22:23,373
The market is figuring it out as it goes by itself.

316
00:22:23,854 --> 00:22:24,074
Right.

317
00:22:24,254 --> 00:22:25,335
Those aren't the technical terms.

318
00:22:25,615 --> 00:22:26,195
It's pretty much.

319
00:22:26,316 --> 00:22:27,376
What are the technical terms?

320
00:22:27,396 --> 00:22:28,918
That's pretty much the technical term.

321
00:22:29,018 --> 00:22:33,521
So no individual knows how much each person would value each good.

322
00:22:34,002 --> 00:22:38,025
So solving who shall get what to create the maximum amount of joy is an incredibly hard problem.

323
00:22:38,105 --> 00:22:41,527
In programming a computer, it would take years for the computer to solve it.

324
00:22:41,547 --> 00:22:43,409
This is just an immensely difficult thing.

325
00:22:44,114 --> 00:22:56,665
But a market is like a big calculator and it can aggregate all of this information and figure out a way by adjusting prices to making sure that each of the goods going to the food banks ends up at the food bank that wants it most.

326
00:22:56,976 --> 00:23:04,862
So what's remarkable is we're looking at one organization, a food bank, and we can see how big the knowledge problem is.

327
00:23:05,643 --> 00:23:11,268
No one at the top of the organization has enough information to be able to make good decisions.

328
00:23:11,368 --> 00:23:21,356
The top of the organization just doesn't know about the solution that the Alaskan food bank has worked out in terms of being able to ship from California.

329
00:23:21,816 --> 00:23:25,939
They don't know how many potatoes the Idaho Food Bank already has.

330
00:23:26,400 --> 00:23:28,241
They just don't have that much information.

331
00:23:28,361 --> 00:23:34,426
And if we think that's hard to have within an organization, imagine if you were trying to do that for the entire economy.

332
00:23:34,706 --> 00:23:38,589
It's a colossal challenge and really no one's up to the task.

333
00:23:38,930 --> 00:23:50,659
Well, some people would probably say, well, you just need more computers and more inventory and more AI learning and figuring out who wants what in some sort of database option.

334
00:23:51,220 --> 00:23:59,146
Bottom line is that the information is too dispersed across society for it to be able to be aggregated together into one person.

335
00:23:59,867 --> 00:24:03,009
But what we do have in markets is prices.

336
00:24:03,570 --> 00:24:07,693
And prices plays the role of helping us aggregate that information.

337
00:24:08,173 --> 00:24:09,494
Price acts as a signal.

338
00:24:10,015 --> 00:24:20,063
So if we view the food bank market as this elegant solution to the problems of distribution they had, and it did work beautifully, but what can go wrong in a market?

339
00:24:20,765 --> 00:24:24,649
Well, there are a number of things that can occur that we call market failures.

340
00:24:25,290 --> 00:24:32,397
But perhaps the most relevant one to think about right now is how market power can undermine competitive pressures.

341
00:24:33,355 --> 00:24:49,264
In a normal market, we can think about a world where we don't have a bunch of different sellers competing with a bunch of different buyers, but perhaps we have only one primary buyer and lots of different sellers.

342
00:24:49,544 --> 00:24:51,285
People worry about that in the labor market.

343
00:24:51,305 --> 00:24:55,467
What if you're in a small town and Walmart's the only employer?

344
00:24:55,487 --> 00:25:00,650
That's one buyer and lots and lots of people trying to get a job.

345
00:25:01,670 --> 00:25:17,938
And so you can think who's going to have power in that relationship, who's going to be able to get a price that benefits them most, who's going to be able to try to extract as much of the benefits from that relationship as possible, it's going to be the one who has market power.

346
00:25:18,498 --> 00:25:25,482
We can think about it on the other side where perhaps there's one seller in many, many different buyers.

347
00:25:26,452 --> 00:25:31,753
Many people have noted that prices on Amazon seem to be going up during the pandemic.

348
00:25:32,454 --> 00:25:35,494
Amazon is a company that seems to have a lot of market power right now.

349
00:25:35,574 --> 00:25:39,575
Lots of people are turning to their computers and trying to order from Amazon.

350
00:25:39,595 --> 00:25:44,096
So you've got lots and lots of different buyers, not one seller.

351
00:25:44,136 --> 00:25:53,459
There's obviously alternatives, but that's a situation where it's easier for a company to extract higher profits out of their customers.

352
00:25:54,309 --> 00:25:59,875
Justin, are there places where a market can never work or shouldn't work?

353
00:25:59,975 --> 00:26:11,408
I mean, I don't know much about your own family, but you don't distribute love coupons that are tradable for hugs, and you don't have that sort of market-based economy just in your family.

354
00:26:12,112 --> 00:26:12,452
Do you?

355
00:26:13,672 --> 00:26:14,453
Currently, we don't.

356
00:26:16,293 --> 00:26:21,775
There's an SEC investigation at the moment of the snuggle market, and we had to suspend trading.

357
00:26:22,655 --> 00:26:26,116
But are there areas where you should not try and enforce a market solution?

358
00:26:26,536 --> 00:26:26,676
Right.

359
00:26:26,716 --> 00:26:31,998
So there are some areas where trust works really, really well, and that's why we do a lot of things in families.

360
00:26:33,712 --> 00:26:38,335
And there are some parts of markets where if people don't have trust, they work really, really poorly.

361
00:26:38,956 --> 00:26:43,479
Economists call this trust problem an information problem because what if you know something that I don't?

362
00:26:44,459 --> 00:26:50,163
If I don't trust you that you would tell me bad news about the product, then I start to worry you're trying to sell me a dud.

363
00:26:50,203 --> 00:26:58,989
So to give a really simple example, lots of people end up buying a used car from an aunt, an uncle, their parents, a brother or a sister.

364
00:26:59,749 --> 00:27:03,432
They do that because they know if it was a really crappy car, they'd probably get told.

365
00:27:04,588 --> 00:27:10,253
Whereas when you go down to the local use car lot, I've never met a used car salesman who said, look, the reason this one's cheap is because it's a dad.

366
00:27:11,374 --> 00:27:11,814
It's a limit.

367
00:27:12,495 --> 00:27:21,182
And so when one person knows something that the other doesn't, and there's not bombs of trust between them, that can really undermine markets.

368
00:27:21,222 --> 00:27:24,705
It's a big deal also in health insurance and healthcare markets as well.

369
00:27:25,063 --> 00:27:30,970
Let me give you another situation where people are typically not comfortable with markets.

370
00:27:31,751 --> 00:27:38,859
And that's for things where people feel like trading, particularly involving cash, would be repugnant.

371
00:27:39,519 --> 00:27:41,962
So we don't have a market for organs.

372
00:27:42,763 --> 00:27:52,147
You might need a new kidney, but it's not okay to go and say, hey, you got two, I'll give you 30 grand for one.

373
00:27:53,288 --> 00:27:57,610
That market is seen as just morally wrong.

374
00:27:57,870 --> 00:28:00,351
Although to be clear, a lot of economists think that's a mistake.

375
00:28:01,191 --> 00:28:04,633
If we offered people 30 grand for kidneys, we might get more kidneys.

376
00:28:04,893 --> 00:28:08,315
So there's this delicate dance between economics and ethics here.

377
00:28:08,995 --> 00:28:10,976
But those are places where

378
00:28:11,905 --> 00:28:20,772
you know, there are real ethical concerns about people who would, you know, think, you know, my, I got to put food on the table for my kids.

379
00:28:21,553 --> 00:28:25,836
And I don't, the market for my labor isn't working out very well.

380
00:28:25,976 --> 00:28:28,158
Maybe I should start selling off a kidney.

381
00:28:29,079 --> 00:28:36,725
That is a reason why there's lots of markets that we have tried to say, you know, we're just not comfortable with this.

382
00:28:37,105 --> 00:28:38,567
The technical term is icky.

383
00:28:40,489 --> 00:28:41,289
Icky.

384
00:28:41,369 --> 00:28:50,599
That's going to be one of our vocabulary words for the day, icky, as well as the phrase local knowledge problem, where people at the top of an organization don't know what's happening down at the bottom.

385
00:28:51,280 --> 00:28:58,527
And the phrase gains from trade, which Justin used, where if you allow people to voluntarily trade, everyone can get happier.

386
00:28:58,607 --> 00:29:00,068
There's just more joy in the world.

